 England","England":"England","Sussex, Angleterre":"Sussex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":7,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Joan Whegleton was born about 1375, in Sussex, England as the daughter of Richard Whegleton and Maud. She married John Fauconer alias Michelgrove about 1397, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died on 30 July 1438, in England, at the age of 64."},"et":{"about 1375–30 July 1438":"umbes 1375–30. juuli 1438","1362–1384":"1362–1384","1373–1420":"1373–1420","1375–1438":"1375–1438","1370–1439":"1370–1439","1398–1459":"1398–1459","1343–1383":"1343–1383","–1386":"–1386","from 1432 to 1439":"1432 kuni 1439","14 September 1383":"14. september 1383","1373":"1373","1384":"1384","1362":"1362","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1459":"1459","1343":"1343","1398":"1398","1420":"1420","30 July 1438":"30. juuli 1438","1386":"1386","1375":"1375","about 1398":"umbes 1398","after 1386":"pärast 1386","about 1375":"umbes 1375","about 1397":"umbes 1397","1439":"1439","1438":"1438","Clapham, Sussex, England":"Clapham, Sussex, England","England":"England","Sussex, Angleterre":"Sussex, England"},"fi":{"about 1375–30 July 1438":"noin 1375–30. heinäkuuta 1438","1362–1384":"1362–1384","1373–1420":"1373–1420","1375–1438":"1375–1438","1370–1439":"1370–1439","1398–1459":"1398–1459","1343–1383":"1343–1383","–1386":"–1386","from 1432 to 1439":"vuodesta 1432 vuoteen 1439","14 September 1383":"14. syyskuuta 1383","1373":"1373","1384":"1384","1362":"1362","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1459":"1459","1343":"1343","1398":"1398","1420":"1420","30 July 1438":"30. heinäkuuta 1438","1386":"1386","1375":"1375","about 1398":"noin 1398","after 1386":"1386 jälkeen","about 1375":"noin 1375","about 1397":"noin 1397","1439":"1439","1438":"1438","Clapham, Sussex, England":"Clapham, Sussex, England","England":"England","Sussex, Angleterre":"Sussex, England"},"fr":{"about 1375–30 July 1438":"